payload.findings1:
• Site assessment currently indicates deliveries should be made via the rear dock, however, the rear door was locked and blocked by bins.
  • Driver confirmed that he has unloaded through the front enrrance in previous deliveries.
  • Store staff advised that deliveries are always completed through the front of the store.
  • Current Process requires the driver to manoeuvre pallets through outside the carpark into the front entrance of shop increasing the risk of collision with displays, stock, or customers.
  • There were multiple 3rd party customers entering the store during unloading, increasing exposure to pedestrian interaction.
  • The tail lift was used for unloading.
  • Store staff did not establish or assist with cone placement to control foot traffic.
payload.summary1:
• The driver was required to unload through the front store entrance as the rear dock was locked and blocked by bins.
  • After lowering pallets using the tail lift, the driver had to manoeuvre them through the front entrance - where there was a risk of interaction with 3rd party pedestrians and nearby vehicles.
  • Once inside, the driver had to navigate around product displays, increasing the risk of contact or damage to store stock.
  • site assessment is not consistent with unloading process which specifies rear dock delivery. Bws staff has advised me that they don't use rear dock and have always receives pallets through the front of store entrance.

Reccomendation:

Review site assessment (feasibility of rear dock access and evaluate risk of unloading pallet through front entrance of store)

payload.details1:
• Site: Australian integrated steel work co (23 mcintyre way, kenwick)
  • Commercial site
  • Activity: unloading full gas cylinders & collecting empty cylinders
  • Vaughn training Mark Barrell (Site supervisor)
payload.findings1:
• Operators both wearing high visibility clothing and gloves.
  • Tail lift operation controlled carefully with workers staying clear of moving platform.
  • Client cylinder racking was rusty, uneven surface when placing cylinders, operator had to secure with strap.
  • Operators demonstrated correct manual handling techniques, no awkward bending, one hand on top of cylinder while other hand to manevour and pushing cylinder.
  • Limited space between the vehicles and work area may restrict safe movement.
  • Vaughn Ovens was conducting on-the-job training with a new Air Liquide supervisor Mark Barrell.
  • Driver 360 conducted after delivery.
payload.summary1:
Task carried out safely with good teamwork. Vaughn was observed handling the cylinders with no awkward posture, he is conscious in avoiding injury.

Speaking to Mark, he has extensive experience handling gas cylinders, particularly servicing medical centres. He is not afraid to get his hands dirty, showing leadership to the drivers.

This site was very congested, AL truck parked adjacent to a site truck. Less distance required from the tail lift to the racking.

payload.details1:
• Site - Woolworths Secret harbour
  • Activity - Unloading 16 pallets & pick up empty pallets
payload.findings1:
• Roadworks on the main route required a detour through a residential area.
  • While turning left on Atmos Road, an overhanging tree created a clearance risk of scraping trailer.
  • Driver slowed, checked mirrors, and reversed carefully to avoid contact, maintaining full awareness and control.
  • Site entry was correctly followed. Driver is aware where site assessments are on bustle app.
  • Reversing area tight with minimal clearance between fence line and parked vehicles (see photo).
  • During reverse, driver maintained slow, controlled manoeuvring with constant mirror checks.
  • Several cars waiting nearby, increasing potential interaction. Driver was signalling cars to stop.
  • Unloading involved 16 pallets into the stores receiving area.
  • Store established a temporary loading exclusion zone during unloading.
  • Loading area was clear of obstructions and hazards.
  • Driver positioning using EPJ was slow and controlled, away from foot and body when maneuvering.
payload.summary1:
On route to Woolworths Secret Harbour, we encountered unplanned roadworks and took a detour through a residential area. The route was clear from overhanging trees, however, when turning left onto Atmos Road, an overhanging tree created a clearance risk.

To avoid the tree clipping the left trailer, The driver managed the situation safely by swinging wide, checking mirrors, and adjusting the turn to avoid contact.

Upon arrival, the reversing area at the site was very tight, requiring the driver to manoeuvre close to a fence and a parked car.

Several cars passed during the manoeuvre, increasing interaction risk, but the driver remained cautious, aware, and in full control thoughout the process (he rated this maneuver a 8/10 in difficulty).

Driver used store electric epj to unload 16 pallets. Epj positioned away from body and foot. Store set up exclusion zone prior.

Upon exit, the driver consistently checked mirrors, with no overhanging branches or obstacles. The site provided wide clearance for a safe and easy departure.

payload.details1:
• Store: Dan Murphy bullcreek
  • Vehicle: Mb54
  • 10 pallets delivered
payload.findings1:
• Accessed site via Benningfield road entering through car park.
  • Trolley was blocking path of exit, driver got out to remove.
  • No designated loading bay truck positioned on other lane for unloading.
  • Dan Murphys staff established a temporary exclusion zone with cones and chains.
  • Ground surface uneven and slightly sloped, creating a risk for for unloading.
  • Driver received 12 stacks of CHEP pallets, which were blocked and contained using epj and pogo sticks.
  • Driver manoeuvred the EPJ within the truck while store staff used forklift to unload pallets.
  • Driver maintained safe positioning while using epj keeping clear of the line of fire from hands, body and foot.
  • Driver maintained three points of contact when climbing on the trailer deck.
  • Store staff was very cautious in ensuring safe transfer of pallets despite uneven ground.
  • Pedestrians remained clear of the exclusion zone during unloading.
  • During departure, the driver continuously checked mirrors and navigated carefully through the car park.
  • Exit route passed Dan Murphys before turning left to the main road. (Need to confirm delivery site assessments was followed).
  • No overhanging tree branches encountered during this run.
payload.summary1:
The driver manoeuvred the EPJ inside the truck while store staff used a forklift to unload maintaining clear communication.

Exclusion controls were effective, and pedestrians remained clear.

Uneven ground during unloading is a risk for store staff.

loading bay requires driver to park on opposite site of lane.

Car park is very tight, requiring driver to be very cautious of surroundings when maneuvering.

Overall driver showed awareness during unloading and when exiting car park.

payload.details1:
Site: 3 take off way, Brabham

vehicle: RC72 (flat deck)
payload.findings1:
• Emilio is new to the business (3 months)
  • Operator wearing hard hat and chin strap while climbing on trailer and operating hiab.
  • Operator displays safe hiab movements (test lift, staying clear from line of fire and suspended load).
  • Operator has used 2 outriggers (parked in even surface)
  • Soft slings are available, no hard slings
  • No side pins are missing
  • passenger side rear mirror missing, when asked the operator says it has been missing for a few months now. Have assisted to fill in defect.
  • Driver 360 conducted
payload.summary1:
• Operator is performing test lifts, staying clear from line of fire and away from suspended load while operating Hiab.
  • Operator has conducted final check on vehicle after loading to ensure loads are strapped and all side pins are in place.
  • Advised operator that passenger side rear mirror is missing, he has not reported this for a few months, have assisted driver in reporting defect and educated him on importance of getting defects repaired.
  • Driver has conducted 360 check and educated on the importance of verifying loads are strapped using this process.

payload.details1:
• Site: 81 Vaughan Cr, Forrestfield
  • Activity: Hiab unload
  • Condition: Wet weather
payload.findings1:
• Cones used to establish an exclusion zone before unloading/loading.
  • Hard hat with chin strap worn when working on top of the truck.
  • Gluts placed under products to prevent damage.
  • Operator took caution when slinging load in wet conditions.
  • Operator maintained 3-points of contact during vehicle access and egress.
  • Operator stopped to allow safe passage of third-party vehicles during slinging on driver side.
  • Appropriate PPE worn, including high-visibility clothing.
  • Load secured prior to lifting, test lift performed.
  • Outrigger used.
  • Driver 360 conducted.
payload.summary1:
Jay demonstrated strong safety awareness throughout the task. Took time to complete the job carefully in wet conditions, double-checking load positioning and performing multi test lifts. Staying away from the line of fire away from a suspended load. After completing his delivery, he did a extensive 360 walk around, ensure loads, gates were secure prior to departing.

Jay showed clear understanding of the increased risks with working in wet conditions, such as slips and reduced footing, and adjusted his approach to ensure safe unload.

When it was heavy rain, Jay did not rush the job, he still took his time to re-strap the load, close the underdeck gates, take photos of product. He displays a strong commitment to his job and is diligent in doing the task correctly and safely.

payload.details1:
• Location : Pressform Engineering ( 23 Jackson Street Bassendean )
  • Driver : Nigel McInerney
  • Vehicle : R58
  • Time : 1300hrs
payload.findings1:
• Delivery of 1 x Pallet and 1 x 9metre pack Aluminium Tubing
  • Continuous traffic movement due to business being on a busy road
  • Minimal unloading area for truck to be unloaded
  • Unloading area directly underneath power Lines
  • No Drivers area whilst truck being unloaded
payload.summary1:
• Driver had customer goods on the drivers side for ease of unloading
  • The loading/unloading area was blocked off by cars parked in the area, and a company vehicle so driver had to park partially on the road and the driveway to be unloaded
  • Client had no safety procedures in place for loading/unloading
  • No traffic cones available to create an exclusion zone around the truck whilst opening the curtains ( Constant Traffic driving past the truck while being unloaded )
  • Truck was parked directly underneath powerlines so the potential was there for the forklift driver to contact the powerlines whilst unloading
  • Due to the limited space and safety procedures in place the driver ensured he was well clear of vehicle while it was being unloaded ( 10mtrs )

payload.summary1:

  • Driver chocked wheels and ensured the area was clear
  • Driver communicated well with site employees that were still operating around the area
  • Driver used correctly all PPE that is required to fulfil the task (Long Sleeve High Vis, Helmet, Face Shield, Earmuffs, Gloves, Steel cap boots )
  • Driver ensured that the power cord has sufficient length to reach plug
  • Knowledge of correct refilling procedure and sequence to safely complete task / refill
  • Using tools provided to undo nuts and caps on vessels ( Pouring water over connections to melt ice )
  • Packing up of all hoses and equipment once task completed
  • Final check to ensure all taps and valves have been closed and all is secured before leaving site
